            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                   <app loc="1">
                       <lem>n<unclear>i</unclear>han· </lem>
                       <note>The vocalization on the first syllable is not clearly visible on any of the available photos.</note>
                   </app>
                    <app loc="1–2"> <!--should use n dash?-->                    
                        <lem>tapak· valaṙ</lem>
                        <note>Many previous scholars read here <foreign>tapak kavali</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <lem>nu syi muliA tapa</lem>
                        <note>We interpret the syntactic structure of this clause as a fuller expression of the same that is seen in Kawali VI <foreign>nu atisti rasa</foreign>. </note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="4">
                        <lem>maṅaḍəg</lem>
                        <note>The shape of ṅa is not carefully engraved. Cf. the more careful execution of this sign in Kawali II, l. 2 <foreign>ṅə</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="6–7"><!--should use n dash?-->     
                        <lem>sakulili</lem>
                        <note>Previous scholars have read <foreign>sakuliliṁ</foreign>, but it may be doubted that any <foreign>anusvāra</foreign>/<foreign>cecak</foreign> was written here.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
           
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
                <p>This is the footprint/These are the footprints (<foreign>tapak walar</foreign>) of the one(s) of praiseworthy asceticism. He, his majesty king Wastu, ruling in the city Kawali, is the one who beautifies the palace Surawisesa, who digs a moat around the city, who plants (crops) in all villages. If there is one in the future, he must do good works, so that success in the world be long-lasting.</p>
            </div>
